<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26262i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26262i">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26262i"> 262(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> sacer</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The XII. Tables]</font>&mdash;In form the laws contained in the Tables were of remarkable brevity, terseness and pregnancy, with something of a rhythmical cadence that must have greatly facilitated their retention in the memory. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The system as a whole is one of <i>jus</i> as distinguished from <i>fas</i>. In the royal laws execration (<i>sacratio capitis</i>, <i><mark>sacer</mark> esto</i>) was a common sanction; but in the Tables it occurs only once pure and simple, and that with reference to an offence that could be committed only by a patrician,&mdash;material loss caused by a patron to his client <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Hanging and beheading, flogging to death, burning at the stake, throwing from the Tarpeian rock,&mdash;such are secular penalties that are met in the Tables <small> &ldquo;ROMAN LAW&rdquo; <a name="EBRL2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRL2"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 538</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
